Scott: Sure.

866
00:48:35,662 --> 00:48:38,173
Scott: So basically earlier in life.

867
00:48:38,494 --> 00:48:38,715
Scott: Right.

868
00:48:38,795 --> 00:48:40,884
Scott: I was we weren't wise in our ways.

869
00:48:40,904 --> 00:48:56,906
Scott: And there were often be situations where, like, you know, you start doing something and due to social pressure or custom or psychology or whatever have you, you sort of feel like, you know, you don't even consider escaping.

870
00:48:57,027 --> 00:48:58,312
Scott: It's like you're in and you're in.

871
00:48:58,372 --> 00:48:59,817
Scott: It's like, I guess I'm doing this now.

872
00:48:59,878 --> 00:49:00,018
Scott: Right.

873
00:49:00,058 --> 00:49:01,424
Scott: You're not even like thinking about it.

874
00:49:01,444 --> 00:49:02,348
Scott: You're just sort of not.

875
00:49:02,388 --> 00:49:04,337
Scott: you're just doing the thing you set out to do.

876
00:49:04,357 --> 00:49:04,457
Scott: Right.

877
00:49:05,320 --> 00:49:12,989
Scott: For example, when we went to New York City to go see Shigeru Miyamoto, we waited in line at the Nintendo store half the day.

878
00:49:13,009 --> 00:49:14,636
Scott: We didn't see him.

879
00:49:14,676 --> 00:49:15,419
Scott: And then we went home.

880
00:49:16,060 --> 00:49:16,282
Scott: Right.

881
00:49:16,884 --> 00:49:18,794
Scott: Well, there was a GeekNights episode about that, I think.

882
00:49:18,854 --> 00:49:19,980
Rym: God, that was a long time ago.

883
00:49:21,180 --> 00:49:21,742
Scott: We could have.

884
00:49:22,044 --> 00:49:27,446
Scott: And it would have been wiser for us to realize the truth, which is that so many people were cutting in line in front of us.

885
00:49:27,908 --> 00:49:29,013
Scott: We were waiting so long.

886
00:49:29,073 --> 00:49:30,037
Scott: They weren't letting us in.

887
00:49:30,057 --> 00:49:31,323
Scott: There was so little information.

888
00:49:31,343 --> 00:49:34,314
Scott: You know, there was going to be a strict limit on the whole thing.

889
00:49:34,334 --> 00:49:37,125
Scott: It was easy to see that we were never going to get in those doors.

890
00:49:37,165 --> 00:49:38,491
Scott: We were not close enough to the front.

891
00:49:39,153 --> 00:49:47,143
Scott: And we would have been able to save time in our lives by simply getting out of that line and going home hours earlier and not wasting a day.

892
00:49:47,163 --> 00:49:48,529
Scott: We could have gone and done something else.

893
00:49:48,569 --> 00:49:56,439
Rym: My moment growing up like I like I had a thing and I think this is a sentiment a lot of people seem to have of if I start reading a book, I'm going to finish it.

894
00:49:57,041 --> 00:50:02,545
Rym: And I remember as a kid for the first time, I started reading a book and I got like the deep way into it.

895
00:50:02,947 --> 00:50:08,007
Rym: And then I made the conscious decision to not read the rest of it because that book sucked.

896
00:50:08,388 --> 00:50:13,851
Rym: And that was like a moderate revelation for me that, oh, I can't I could just stop.

897
00:50:13,911 --> 00:50:15,940
Rym: I don't have to follow through on something that sucks.

898
00:50:16,981 --> 00:50:24,051
Scott: Right now, it's a little tricky because I sort of also have the opposite problem, right, which is something I really do honestly want to finish.

899
00:50:24,251 --> 00:50:24,372
Scott: Right.

900
00:50:24,392 --> 00:50:26,320
Scott: You're working on a thing you want to work on.

901
00:50:26,560 --> 00:50:29,794
Scott: You know, maybe some podcast or maybe, you know, maybe you're making something right.

902
00:50:29,995 --> 00:50:32,485
Scott: You want to do this and you just can't finish it.

903
00:50:32,545 --> 00:50:32,806
Scott: Right.

904
00:50:32,866 --> 00:50:35,898
Scott: So it's like and it's you can't even get yourself to work on it.

905
00:50:35,938 --> 00:50:37,203
Scott: It's like the opposite problem.

906
00:50:37,223 --> 00:50:37,344
Scott: Right.

907
00:50:37,364 --> 00:50:37,926
Scott: You can't get in.

908
00:50:39,071 --> 00:50:41,240
Scott: You want to get over the finish line, but you can't finish.

909
00:50:41,621 --> 00:50:49,875
Scott: So because you have that problem when you're in a situation where you're headed towards the finish line and it's like you don't want to bail.

910
00:50:50,236 --> 00:50:50,437
Scott: Right.

911
00:50:50,457 --> 00:50:51,661
Scott: You sort of can get the mix.

912
00:50:51,681 --> 00:50:57,284
Scott: You really have to evaluate is that, you know, look at what you're in for.

913
00:50:57,645 --> 00:50:57,846
Scott: Right.

914
00:50:57,946 --> 00:50:58,649
Scott: Are you stuck?

915
00:50:58,749 --> 00:51:00,857
Scott: Are you staying just because you think you have to stay?

916
00:51:00,938 --> 00:51:02,042
Scott: Are you enjoying yourself?

917
00:51:02,122 --> 00:51:03,287
Scott: Is this really what you want?

918
00:51:03,949 --> 00:51:09,751
Scott: And, you know, be able to strongly commit or quit as soon as possible.

919
00:51:09,811 --> 00:51:11,196
Scott: That's that's the longer you go.

920
00:51:11,256 --> 00:51:12,541
Rym: You got to make that decision.

921
00:51:12,561 --> 00:51:13,325
Scott: And it's really not.

922
00:51:13,405 --> 00:51:16,540
Rym: it's not easy because otherwise you fall in the sunk cost fallacy.

923
00:51:16,701 --> 00:51:19,391
Rym: Like, well, I've been standing here for four hours.

924
00:51:19,591 --> 00:51:24,089
Rym: I might as well stick around because there's a chance that Miyamoto is going to sign myself a two cartridge.

925
00:51:25,775 --> 00:51:27,944
Rym: But the reality was the chance was so low.

926
00:51:28,848 --> 00:51:36,177
Rym: If you and the longer you wait before you bail, the more cost you have paid in time or money or energy or something.

927
00:51:36,780 --> 00:51:38,125
Rym: And the outcome was the same.

928
00:51:38,206 --> 00:51:41,620
Rym: So if there's even a chance you're going to bail on something, you've got to make that decision.

929
00:51:42,240 --> 00:51:42,863
Rym: ASAP.

930
00:51:44,007 --> 00:51:44,148
Scott: Yeah.

931
00:51:44,188 --> 00:51:49,650
Scott: The sooner you bail, if bailing was the right choice, the sooner you bail, the better off you are.

932
00:51:49,831 --> 00:51:50,052
Scott: Right.

933
00:51:50,092 --> 00:51:53,686
Scott: If you wait 10 more minutes and then bail, well, you just lost those 10 minutes.

934
00:51:53,787 --> 00:51:54,068
Scott: Right.

935
00:51:54,088 --> 00:51:56,600
Scott: You could have just decided the same thing earlier.

936
00:51:57,381 --> 00:52:00,754
Rym: Now, I remember RIT because this problem happened a lot.

937
00:52:00,795 --> 00:52:07,300
Rym: Like, I'm not going to try to get into all the different anecdotes, but where we would decide to do something as a group, it kind of sucked.

938
00:52:07,581 --> 00:52:09,409
Rym: Or like one person really wanted to do something.

939
00:52:09,670 --> 00:52:10,955
Rym: The rest of us weren't super into it.

940
00:52:11,156 --> 00:52:12,120
Rym: We go along with it anyway.

941
00:52:12,521 --> 00:52:13,465
Rym: It's actually not great.

942
00:52:13,505 --> 00:52:14,368
Rym: We all stick around.

943
00:52:14,388 --> 00:52:17,400
Rym: And there was an episode, I guess, South Park came up again.

944
00:52:17,760 --> 00:52:21,094
Rym: The trifecta will come when it comes up a third time around that time.

945
00:52:21,114 --> 00:52:27,561
Rym: And when we used to be watching South Park, an episode dropped the return of the Fellowship of the Ring of the Two Towers or whatever.

946
00:52:27,581 --> 00:52:32,942
Rym: And in that episode, a character has a moment where he learns the truth about his situation.

947
00:52:33,364 --> 00:52:36,999
Rym: He walks out and he makes his hand gesture and he's just like, I'm out.

948
00:52:38,302 --> 00:52:38,985
Rym: And they're like, what?

949
00:52:39,065 --> 00:52:40,130
Rym: And he's just like, I'm out.

950
00:52:40,391 --> 00:52:42,059
Rym: And then he leaves and that's it.

951
00:52:43,022 --> 00:52:49,304
Rym: And at RIT, Scott and I very consciously made the decision to make that a thing in our group.

952
00:52:49,385 --> 00:52:54,646
Rym: We started to, whenever we had two things, we'd either bail by saying, I'm out.

953
00:52:54,927 --> 00:52:55,549
Rym: Like, we're done.

954
00:52:55,609 --> 00:52:56,192
Rym: This is over.

955
00:52:56,894 --> 00:52:58,299
Rym: Or it's all you.

956
00:52:58,721 --> 00:53:08,400
Rym: Where if we chose not to bail, whoever was the person who was advocating for not bailing, it's all you means you are now responsible for any misery that follows.

957
00:53:09,401 --> 00:53:13,860
Rym: But if you are correct and our instinct to bail was wrong, you get all the glory.

958
00:53:14,040 --> 00:53:16,290
Rym: You were the one who got us this experience.

959
00:53:16,672 --> 00:53:19,462
Rym: I don't think anyone ever was the.

960
00:53:19,543 --> 00:53:20,166
Rym: it's all you.

961
00:53:20,186 --> 00:53:22,319
Rym: And it was good for them in the long run.

962
00:53:24,060 --> 00:53:25,451
Scott: You're usually the all you.

963
00:53:25,793 --> 00:53:26,599
Scott: It's usually all you.

964
00:53:26,860 --> 00:53:26,961
Rym: Yeah.

965
00:53:27,142 --> 00:53:29,919
Rym: And a lot of the things that we tried to do did not work out so great.

966
00:53:33,401 --> 00:53:38,145
Rym: But we became like especially like I have a very well-known among my friends.

967
00:53:38,828 --> 00:53:41,860
Rym: My bail tolerance is like a hair trigger.

968
00:53:42,361 --> 00:53:46,360
Rym: Like, you know, I'm walking to a Starbucks and there's more than one person in line.

969
00:53:46,460 --> 00:53:47,343
Rym: I just walk right back out.

970
00:53:48,367 --> 00:53:51,940
Scott: Your bail tolerance has gone to the extreme in the other direction.

971
00:53:52,000 --> 00:53:52,643
Scott: A little too far.

972
00:53:52,663 --> 00:53:54,250
Scott: You got to bring it back.

973
00:53:55,576 --> 00:53:56,500
Scott: You know, it's like they'll be sick.

974
00:53:56,540 --> 00:54:02,580
Scott: It's like, yeah, if I'm going to a restaurant and it's way full and there's people just packed out front, it's like, OK, we're not waiting to eat here.

975
00:54:02,800 --> 00:54:03,082
Scott: Right.

976
00:54:03,564 --> 00:54:06,399
Scott: But there'll be a place with like, you know, it's full.

977
00:54:06,940 --> 00:54:09,614
Scott: There's like one group waiting in front of us and we'll be like bail.

978
00:54:09,694 --> 00:54:10,880
Scott: And I'm like, there's one group.

979
00:54:10,940 --> 00:54:12,854
Scott: We're going to be sitting in like 15, 20 hours.

980
00:54:13,820 --> 00:54:16,330
Rym: But I've been in situations where that delicious food is here.

981
00:54:16,371 --> 00:54:18,640
Scott: It's going to be what I've been in situations in front of us.

982
00:54:18,820 --> 00:54:28,160
Rym: Like, fuck you, Sukkotai, where there was an open table and they told us 15 minutes multiple times over the course of an hour and did not give us a table.

983
00:54:28,500 --> 00:54:28,761
Scott: Right.

984
00:54:29,042 --> 00:54:34,800
Scott: But at that point, it's like, yeah, if I see the open table and then I wait 10 minutes and if they don't give it to me when I ask, then I bail.

985
00:54:35,020 --> 00:54:35,140
Scott: Right.

986
00:54:35,161 --> 00:54:36,867
Scott: But you're you're at the point where you're bailing.

987
00:54:36,907 --> 00:54:40,440
Scott: Like you walk in, you'll take you'll like take a snapshot of the scene and then leave.

988
00:54:40,541 --> 00:54:41,958
Rym: It's like, give it 30 seconds.

989
00:54:42,320 --> 00:54:44,230
Rym: I think part of what part of what happened there is.

990
00:54:44,311 --> 00:54:46,000
Rym: I do this particularly with restaurants.

991
00:54:46,561 --> 00:55:02,160
Rym: And I think it's an artifact of living in New York, especially in a neighborhood full of great restaurants for so long, that if there is even the slightest bit of resistance walking into a restaurant that I like, there are 10 other restaurants I like just as much within a 15 second walk of that door.

992
00:55:02,340 --> 00:55:09,420
Scott: I think another problem is that with restaurants specifically, right, if you are currently looking for a restaurant, you are hungry.

993
00:55:09,680 --> 00:55:09,740
Rym: Yup.

994
00:55:09,760 --> 00:55:12,980
Rym: And hungry is just a few minutes away from hangry.

995
00:55:13,982 --> 00:55:14,484
Scott: That's right.

996
00:55:14,504 --> 00:55:17,800
Scott: So you're less tolerant of waiting in that situation.

997
00:55:18,201 --> 00:55:21,911
Rym: If I'm hungry, I will go from let's eat at this restaurant to.

998
00:55:22,152 --> 00:55:25,020
Rym: I'm just going to buy four Gatorades from this deli.

999
00:55:25,361 --> 00:55:26,564
Rym: And that is my dinner.

1000
00:55:27,165 --> 00:55:32,840
Rym: I will bail two Gatorades and stickers like faster than I will wait an hour to sit down at a restaurant.

1001
00:55:33,240 --> 00:55:33,764
Rym: Right.

1002
00:55:33,784 --> 00:55:33,986
Scott: Right.

1003
00:55:34,006 --> 00:55:35,800
Scott: So don't bail that as much as Rym is bailing.

1004
00:55:36,140 --> 00:55:43,360
Scott: But there are plenty of situations, you know, most notably, I think, is, you know, the tabletop game is the one we bring up all the time.

1005
00:55:43,781 --> 00:55:44,002
Scott: Right.

1006
00:55:44,262 --> 00:55:50,940
Scott: You if you're playing a tabletop game with people, you sort of have this obligation that like you're not supposed to quit.

1007
00:55:51,141 --> 00:55:51,361
Scott: Right.

1008
00:55:51,421 --> 00:56:08,960
Scott: It's like even if you've already lost, if the game is over, if you're not having a good time, if one of the other people sucks as a jerk, if people are playing slowly, if you have to go, you know, to somewhere legitimately, there's this sort of social obligation that like you feel like you can't leave.

1009
00:56:09,060 --> 00:56:09,682
Scott: You have to stay.

1010
00:56:09,702 --> 00:56:12,090
Scott: It's like, no, you absolutely can leave.

1011
00:56:12,270 --> 00:56:15,160
Scott: Even if the other people are upset, you can leave.

1012
00:56:15,541 --> 00:56:15,822
Scott: Right.

1013
00:56:16,083 --> 00:56:16,866
Scott: You should leave.

1014
00:56:17,007 --> 00:56:20,040
Scott: If you have any reason whatsoever to leave, leave.

1015
00:56:20,440 --> 00:56:20,721
Rym: Yeah.

1016
00:56:20,761 --> 00:56:30,180
Rym: Well, the way the way I actually look at that with games in particular, like a board game is there's like there's different like there's the mood where, say, five people are playing a game.

1017
00:56:30,841 --> 00:56:34,009
Rym: One person is not having a great time, but they committed to playing.

1018
00:56:34,029 --> 00:56:40,852
Rym: the game is a moderately different situation from something I see very commonly where nobody is having a good time.

1019
00:56:41,073 --> 00:56:42,520
Rym: Literally no one in the game is having a good time.

1020
00:56:42,560 --> 00:56:47,140
Scott: In either situation, either the one, you know, in the first situation, the one person should bail.

1021
00:56:47,260 --> 00:56:51,060
Scott: In the second situation, everyone should collectively be like, yeah, you know, I don't want to play anymore.

1022
00:56:51,120 --> 00:56:52,469
Scott: And everyone will say, yeah, you know what?

1023
00:56:52,589 --> 00:56:53,797
Scott: We all don't want to play anymore.

1024
00:56:53,837 --> 00:56:54,340
Scott: Just put it away.

1025
00:56:54,480 --> 00:56:57,779
Scott: But the one I see the most common is... Bailing is the solution either way.

1026
00:56:57,940 --> 00:57:03,255
Rym: The one I see the most in most common in board games is one person is having a good time.

1027
00:57:03,616 --> 00:57:05,140
Rym: The rest of the table is not.

1028
00:57:05,641 --> 00:57:12,060
Rym: And usually the person who's having a good time, the bail wasn't during the game was actually too late to bail.

1029
00:57:12,460 --> 00:57:19,780
Rym: The problem is actually that all the people in that game agreed to play the game in the first place, but didn't actually want to.

1030
00:57:19,940 --> 00:57:26,720
Rym: They foresaw this situation, but they went along with it anyway, and then they reaped exactly what they sowed.

1031
00:57:27,380 --> 00:57:33,700
Rym: Usually the person who's having a good time is the person who is aggressively trying to recruit people to play that game.

1032
00:57:35,401 --> 00:57:37,369
Rym: Like, not the third South Park.

1033
00:57:37,670 --> 00:57:39,156
Rym: Another relevant South Park episode.

1034
00:57:39,457 --> 00:57:40,140
Rym: The zip lining.

1035
00:57:40,820 --> 00:57:46,340
Rym: Where one person aggressively convinced other people to do the thing that sucked that no one liked.

1036
00:57:46,820 --> 00:57:53,020
Rym: Be wary of anyone who is aggressively selling you on playing a board game with them at a convention.

1037
00:57:53,440 --> 00:57:55,499
Rym: There is a reason why they are trying so hard.

1038
00:57:56,962 --> 00:58:01,660
Scott: I always find it interesting, there's so many overeager people who really want to do something.

1039
00:58:02,120 --> 00:58:05,780
Scott: But those overeager people can't all find each other to form a group of overeager people.

1040
00:58:06,021 --> 00:58:06,424
Rym: Oh, I've seen.

1041
00:58:06,464 --> 00:58:06,666
Rym: I swear.

1042
00:58:08,800 --> 00:58:12,320
Scott: That would be the perfect scenario for those people, but they somehow can't make it happen.

1043
00:58:13,041 --> 00:58:16,780
Rym: So one thing that happens is sometimes those people overlap a little bit with that guy.

1044
00:58:17,181 --> 00:58:23,640
Rym: And the only thing that that guy hates more than being excluded is being included by another that guy.

1045
00:58:25,180 --> 00:58:33,820
Rym: But in terms of the games, not to get into that topic, I feel like usually what happens is those people are all really jazzed about different games.

1046
00:58:35,340 --> 00:58:37,326
Scott: That can happen.

1047
00:58:37,426 --> 00:58:46,136
Scott: So if your friends want to go walking up a mountain and every single friend is going up the mountain, and you don't like going up the mountain, you can just stay home like I did.

1048
00:58:46,237 --> 00:58:46,799
Scott: You don't have to go.

1049
00:58:47,180 --> 00:58:49,008
Scott: No one's making you go.

1050
00:58:49,470 --> 00:58:51,520
Scott: And look, those people are still my friend, I think.

1051
00:58:52,388 --> 00:58:53,519
