Scott: A tornado hit my house.

1159
01:04:17,470 --> 01:04:19,083
Rym: Like, here's here is why we're not coming.

1160
01:04:19,143 --> 01:04:19,970
Rym: Here's the situation.

1161
01:04:20,313 --> 01:04:21,290
Rym: Let's discuss alternative.

1162
01:04:21,451 --> 01:04:22,657
Rym: Like there's there's a whole.

1163
01:04:22,677 --> 01:04:25,350
Rym: or like another example, esports, like don't quit a game, right?

1164
01:04:25,771 --> 01:04:30,950
Rym: If I just play Overwatch, I go to a random casual mode and then I just I'm bored and I just quit.

1165
01:04:31,190 --> 01:04:33,530
Rym: Like, sure, that doesn't impact other people that much.

1166
01:04:33,992 --> 01:04:35,380
Rym: And I didn't commit that much.

1167
01:04:35,441 --> 01:04:37,010
Rym: I was playing in the random mode anyway.

1168
01:04:37,551 --> 01:04:46,430
Rym: But if I affirmatively choose to join the competitive queue to play a competitive game, there is an implicit contract that I agree to finish the game I get put in.

1169
01:04:47,071 --> 01:04:54,570
Rym: So it's a materially different situation to bail on that competitive game because I knew going in what I was committing to.

1170
01:04:57,532 --> 01:05:02,870
Rym: But I feel like generally people should bail more often than they do.

1171
01:05:03,070 --> 01:05:13,690
Rym: I feel like a lot of people choose not to bail on things either out of misplaced senses of commitment or more often misplaced optimism about how that thing will go down.

1172
01:05:14,492 --> 01:05:18,746
Scott: Or misplaced or misinterpreted obligation or false obligation.

1173
01:05:20,070 --> 01:05:21,679
Scott: For example, let's say you're at work, right?

1174
01:05:21,699 --> 01:05:23,610
Scott: I'm not going to talk about quitting work anymore.

1175
01:05:24,031 --> 01:05:27,830
Scott: Let's say you're at work and someone puts a meeting on your calendar.

1176
01:05:28,552 --> 01:05:29,579
Scott: You know, it's and it's a boss.

1177
01:05:29,660 --> 01:05:31,130
Scott: A boss puts a meeting on your calendar.

1178
01:05:31,712 --> 01:05:34,369
Scott: You can say, no, you don't you don't have to go.

1179
01:05:35,431 --> 01:05:36,439
Scott: It's like too many meetings.

1180
01:05:36,479 --> 01:05:38,050
Scott: You know, you don't even need an excuse.

1181
01:05:38,251 --> 01:05:40,404
Scott: You can just say like, no, I'm not going to that meeting.

1182
01:05:40,747 --> 01:05:41,129
Scott: I can't go.

1183
01:05:41,772 --> 01:05:42,455
Scott: No one's going to make you.

1184
01:05:42,576 --> 01:05:45,389
Scott: No one's probably not going to fire you right for something like that.

1185
01:05:45,751 --> 01:05:46,035
Scott: Right.

1186
01:05:46,055 --> 01:05:47,127
Scott: It's like you don't got to go.

1187
01:05:48,151 --> 01:05:54,090
Scott: You know, someone says, hey, you know, you say you're working at the office and it comes around.

1188
01:05:54,210 --> 01:05:59,030
Scott: It's like five o'clock and someone comes up and is like, hey, we got this thing we got to do.

1189
01:05:59,291 --> 01:06:00,797
Scott: You can be like, you know, not to quit.

1190
01:06:01,300 --> 01:06:03,529
Scott: You might get fired depending on how shitty your job is.

1191
01:06:04,051 --> 01:06:06,730
Scott: But, you know, if they say, hey, can you do this one more thing?

1192
01:06:06,770 --> 01:06:08,621
Scott: You can be like, no, I'm good.

1193
01:06:08,662 --> 01:06:09,346
Scott: It's five o'clock.

1194
01:06:09,386 --> 01:06:09,990
Scott: I got to go home.

1195
01:06:10,070 --> 01:06:10,633
Scott: I got to go.

1196
01:06:10,713 --> 01:06:11,799
Scott: My kid's going to be home.

1197
01:06:11,879 --> 01:06:13,870
Scott: I got to you know, I got stuff to do.

1198
01:06:14,030 --> 01:06:14,775
Scott: I got to cook food.

1199
01:06:14,815 --> 01:06:16,425
Scott: See, you know, you got to deal with that.

1200
01:06:16,445 --> 01:06:17,190
Scott: That's not my problem.

1201
01:06:17,430 --> 01:06:18,174
Rym: Yeah.

1202
01:06:18,696 --> 01:06:21,870
Scott: But the optimism thing is pressured into doing something you don't got to do.

1203
01:06:22,070 --> 01:06:27,269
Scott: Don't make it you know, don't make yourself feel like you must do something that you must not do.

1204
01:06:27,530 --> 01:06:27,791
Scott: Yeah.

1205
01:06:27,872 --> 01:06:28,153
Scott: Right.

1206
01:06:28,916 --> 01:06:32,370
Scott: Of course, you know, accurately evaluate the real consequences.

1207
01:06:32,911 --> 01:06:33,151
Scott: Right.

1208
01:06:33,452 --> 01:06:42,350
Scott: You know, some people, I think, imagine consequences that aren't real or imagine consequences to be worse than what they might really be.

1209
01:06:42,530 --> 01:06:43,597
Scott: It's like, yeah, OK.

1210
01:06:43,658 --> 01:06:45,450
Scott: You know, at your job, there might be a shitty.

1211
01:06:45,630 --> 01:06:53,370
Scott: There are definitely shitty jobs out there where someone will just fire you for just going home at the hour you're supposed to go home instead of doing the extra work.

1212
01:06:53,491 --> 01:06:53,732
Scott: Right.

1213
01:06:53,994 --> 01:06:56,350
Scott: But is that really what's going to happen?

1214
01:06:56,671 --> 01:06:56,892
Scott: Right.

1215
01:06:57,233 --> 01:07:03,070
Scott: Is someone maybe going to come to you tomorrow and give you a stir in talking to like, hey, why didn't you do that thing?

1216
01:07:03,210 --> 01:07:04,192
Scott: You're not a team player.

1217
01:07:04,252 --> 01:07:04,413
Scott: Right.

1218
01:07:04,453 --> 01:07:11,950
Scott: It's like, well, could you just, you know, quietly hear them say that and say sorry and you still have your job.

1219
01:07:12,792 --> 01:07:15,382
Scott: So someone gives you a bad evaluation at work.

1220
01:07:15,422 --> 01:07:16,084
Scott: That could happen.

1221
01:07:16,145 --> 01:07:17,470
Scott: It's like, do you still have your job?

1222
01:07:17,911 --> 01:07:18,513
Scott: Do you care?

1223
01:07:18,633 --> 01:07:19,597
Scott: It's just a piece of paper.

1224
01:07:19,918 --> 01:07:20,058
Scott: Right.

1225
01:07:20,099 --> 01:07:21,263
Scott: With a with a thing on it.

1226
01:07:21,403 --> 01:07:21,564
Scott: Right.

1227
01:07:21,604 --> 01:07:23,310
Scott: It's like, do you care about that?

1228
01:07:24,131 --> 01:07:25,455
Scott: Maybe you do care about that.

1229
01:07:25,515 --> 01:07:25,756
Scott: Right.

1230
01:07:25,796 --> 01:07:26,318
Scott: But I don't.

1231
01:07:26,719 --> 01:07:30,150
Scott: So it's like you had to consider what are the real consequences.

1232
01:07:30,831 --> 01:07:32,114
Scott: Are you willing to suffer them?

1233
01:07:32,295 --> 01:07:33,518
Scott: Are they really that bad?

1234
01:07:33,538 --> 01:07:34,079
Scott: Right.

1235
01:07:35,162 --> 01:07:38,170
Scott: Sometimes it's hard to realistically predict consequences.

1236
01:07:38,410 --> 01:07:39,272
Scott: Yeah.

1237
01:07:39,613 --> 01:07:41,578
Scott: But, you know, maybe you can just ask.

1238
01:07:41,998 --> 01:07:42,219
Scott: Right.

1239
01:07:42,279 --> 01:07:47,070
Scott: If someone says, hey, you want to do this, stay late and do this work and be like, well, what what if it doesn't get done?

1240
01:07:47,130 --> 01:07:47,652
Scott: What will happen?

1241
01:07:47,792 --> 01:07:51,281
Scott: Just ask, you know, honestly be like, hey, what what will happen if we just let that go till tomorrow?

1242
01:07:52,946 --> 01:07:54,410
Scott: Is that consequence really that bad?

1243
01:07:54,950 --> 01:08:00,002
Scott: You know, because if I stay and do it, here's what's going to happen to my life.

1244
01:08:00,103 --> 01:08:00,564
Scott: Right.

1245
01:08:00,945 --> 01:08:03,110
Rym: And it also gets complicated by what your goals are.

1246
01:08:03,510 --> 01:08:08,350
Rym: So GeekNights, we bailed on a few shows recently just because we can finally see some of our friends together.

1247
01:08:08,511 --> 01:08:11,523
Rym: And like that's a that's a laser that I need to.

1248
01:08:11,865 --> 01:08:13,070
Rym: it's been charging for over a year.

1249
01:08:13,351 --> 01:08:17,450
Rym: Like that is a higher priority in my life than doing some individual GeekNights episode.

1250
01:08:18,090 --> 01:08:28,069
Rym: But at the same time, when we started GeekNights, we agreed that we would try not to bail and do the Penny Arcade model of just crank the show out no matter what, even if it sucks.

1251
01:08:28,470 --> 01:08:30,316
Rym: And that's how we'll force ourselves to get better.

1252
01:08:30,756 --> 01:08:33,243
Scott: So we'd try to cross.

1253
01:08:33,304 --> 01:08:35,770
Scott: Let me cross the line of where it's not a problem anymore.

1254
01:08:36,151 --> 01:08:39,790
Rym: But we do try not to bail on the show unless we have a good reason.

1255
01:08:40,231 --> 01:08:44,930
Rym: But if we have a good reason, like Scott and I will discuss, like, hey, should we bail on the show?

1256
01:08:45,330 --> 01:08:48,700
Rym: And we we like we try to make that decision immediately.

1257
01:08:48,901 --> 01:08:51,970
Rym: Like if we're going to bail on a show, we make the decision as early as possible.

1258
01:08:52,189 --> 01:08:53,356
Rym: That's we're not going to show that day.

1259
01:08:53,577 --> 01:08:54,542
Rym: We don't even worry about it.

1260
01:08:54,804 --> 01:08:55,426
Rym: We walk away.

1261
01:08:55,488 --> 01:08:55,870
Rym: We're fine.

1262
01:08:56,732 --> 01:08:59,290
Scott: But there's no consequences for not doing a GeekNights episode.

1263
01:08:59,710 --> 01:09:06,010
Rym: But putting that pressure on ourselves to not bail early on was a very powerful tool to make us get good in a hurry.

1264
01:09:06,491 --> 01:09:07,675
Rym: And there are pros and cons to that.

1265
01:09:07,955 --> 01:09:12,988
Rym: But the fact that we chose it and we could have bailed, we chose not to.

